Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
02:30 PM Defendant Robert Thomas Ely in court, in custody.  Clifford C. Burdon appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
  Court advises defendant of right to an attorney.  Defendant understands.  Defendant waives his right to counsel.  Court questions defendant and finds the waiver is being made freely, voluntarily & intelligently.  All parties have received the Revocation Packet and are prepared to proceed.
Atty Burdon makes sentencing recommendation.  

BY THE COURT:   Court sentences defendant to serve 4 years in the Wisconsin Prison System, consecutive to any other sentence, as follows:  1 year Initial Confinement followed by 3 years Extended Supervision.  Granted 121 days credit.  Sentence to commence forthwith.  
Conditions of ES: 
*Pay unpaid costs.  If not paid during Extended Supervision, they are to be converted to a civil judgment
*Maintain absolute sobriety, no possession or consumption of alcohol or controlled substances
*Submit to random UA's
*Comply with any recommendations by the agent
*Not eligible for Earned Release or Challenge Incarceration Programs
Sentencing hearing on revocation on November 30, 2021 at 02:30 pm.

Defendant Robert Thomas Ely in court with attorney Jeanne Lila Zamzow.  Defendant Robert Thomas Ely in custody.  Chad A. Hendee appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Atty Zamzow states that there is an offer to resolve the case but asks for some time to go over the plea questionnaire.

BACK ON THE RECORD:
  Atty Hendee states plea agreement.  Atty Zamzow agrees.  Defendant agrees and enters a No Contest plea.
  Court questions defendant regarding plea. Advises of Constitutional Rights and elements of the charge.  Court finds plea made knowingly, voluntarily & Intelligently.  Court relies on the criminal complaint for a factual basis.  

BY THE COURT:  Court finds a sufficient factual basis to support the charges.  Court accepts defendant's plea and finds defendant guilty.

Atty Hendee requests that the firearms that were siezed be ordered to be destroyed and not turned over to his family.
Atty Zamzow asks that the firearms be turned over to his sister since they were his father's.  Atty Zamzow makes sentencing arguments.
Defendant asks the court to turn the firearms over to his sister.

BY THE COURT: Withhold Sentence; 24 months Probation with conditions; consecutive to his current sentence in Waushara County 16CF98:
